Today, Governor John Bel Edwards announced the guidelines for Phase Three, which goes into effect today. This new order will expire ‚Ä™on Oct. 9th (28 days from now).‚Ä¨ Phase Three includes the following COVID restrictions:

üò∑ Mask mandate will remain in place throughout the state.

ü•ÇBars remain closed for on premise consumption in Jefferson Parish because we do not meet the 5% positivity threshold set forth by the Governor (Parishes with a positivity rate of 5% or lower for two consecutive weeks may opt-in to open bars for on premises consumption).

üç∏ Alcohol sales and service for on premises consumption will end at 10 p.m. everywhere (this includes restaurants, casinos and bars when they reopen).

üè¢Businesses (restaurants, churches, salons, spas, gyms, etc.) are allowed to open at 75% occupancy with social distancing.

üíí üéÇ Events - weddings, birthday parties, etc. (indoors & outdoors) are limited to 50% capacity or 250 people with social distancing.

üèà‚öæÔ∏è Sporting events are limited to 25% capacity and no alcohol sales.

Jefferson Parish, in partnership with The Blood Center, will be hosting a blood drive Saturday, Sept. 12 at Johnny Bright Playground (3401 Cleary Ave., Metairie, LA 70002) from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.

ü©∏ Once donors make an appointment, they should visit ‚ÄúFastlane‚Äù at www.thebloodcenter.org/fastlane after 12:01 a.m. on the day they plan to donate to complete medical questions. All individuals should eat a good meal before donating and bring their ID to the site. When donors arrive to the site, they will have their temperature checked and will be screened for COVID-19 symptoms. Once qualified, they will be assigned a number and be spaced out for social distancing purposes.

Test results for antibody testing will be available after 48 hours. Blood donors must give their email address. They will then be instructed to set up a blood donor account to access their test results. Test results are not given via email, snail mail or phone call, in order to not violate HIPAA regulations.

Intake procedures and protocols at the Jefferson Parish East Bank Animal Shelter located at #1 Humane Way Jefferson, LA 70123, have changed temporarily to accommodate overflow housing for pets of Hurricane Laura evacuees.

Strays brought into the East Bank Animal Shelter during this time will be transferred to the West Bank Animal Shelter for housing after intake and processing. When possible, please notify the East Bank Shelter ahead of bringing in an animal by calling (504) 736-6111. For all animal control service inquiries during normal business hours, please contact the West Bank Shelter at (504) 349-5111. After hours, call 9-1-1 and animal control will be notified.

For more information about the Jefferson Parish Animal Shelter, please call the East Bank Shelter at (504) 736-6111 or the West Bank Shelter at (504) 349-5111.

Happy #TerrificTuesday!‚ú®

Today, we would like to recognize and congratulate our Jefferson Parish Environmental Affairs Department and Storm Water Management Supervisor, Sami Khalil.

Our Environmental Affairs Department was selected as a winner of the Water Environment Federation (WEF)‚Äôs National Municipal Stormwater and Green Infrastructure Awards Program. Sami summited and received ‚ÄúSilver Level in Innovation‚Äù and ‚ÄúGold Level in Project Management‚Äù. This level was selected on rigorous review by the work team and provides a comparative benchmarking level for our community among other 2020 applicants.

WEF is a global not-for-profit technical and educational organization of 43,000 individual members and 75 affiliated Member Associations representing water quality professionals around the world to protect public health and the environment.

Congratulations on this honor! You have served Jefferson Parish proudly. #TerrificTuesday

Thanks to all who have been donating items to our relief drive for those impacted by Hurricane Laura, including our JP employees who have been filling up this cart in the lobby of our Yenni building!

As a reminder, this drive will run through Sunday, Sept. 13.
Individuals should drop off items at the Odom Building, 5001 West Bank Expwy. in Marrero or Jefferson Parish Surplus Property, 920 David Dr. in Metairie.

Items most needed at this time include: Bleach, disinfectants, gloves, scrub brushes, sponges, trash bags, paper towels, tooth brushes, buckets, personal toiletries, diapers, canned food (pop tops if possible), peanut butter, box cereals, protein bars/granola bars, water, sport drinks, packaged snacks, nutritional/healthy drinks (Ensure/PediaSure), baby wipes and feminine products.

We will share more info. soon about another relief drive from JPRD to start on Tuesday!

There will be no garbage collection in unincorporated Jefferson Parish and the Town of Jean Lafitte on Monday, September 7, 2020. Curbside recycling collection will take place, as scheduled on Monday, September 7, 2020. Residents normally scheduled to have garbage pick-up on a Monday will not have their garbage picked up until Thursday, September 10, 2020. There will be no make-up day for the missed holiday collection.

The Jefferson Parish Landfill will remain closed, until further notice. All four Trash Drop-Off sites will close on Monday, September 7, 2020 and will re-open for business on Tuesday, September 8, 2020. Residents wishing to dispose of garbage/trash between curbside collections are reminded that all Parish Trash Drop-Off sites are open Tuesday through Sunday from 10 a.m. ‚Äì 6:30 p.m. (daylight savings hours), except for designated holidays.

For more information, please contact the Jefferson Parish Department of Environmental Affairs at (504)731-4612.

For this #TerrificTuesday, we would like to recognize and thank all our Jefferson Parish Departments who continue to work hard to respond to the needs of those impacted by Hurricane Laura.

üö® Our Emergency Management team organized a Welcome Center for Hurricane Laura evacuees at the Shrine on Airline with the help of our Streets Department, Parkways Department, General Services Department and Traffic Engineering Department.

üöí Our Fire Services Department has multiple Volunteer Fire Departments out responding to needs in Southwest Louisiana.

üê∂ Our Animal Shelter staff were deployed to assist in evacuations, they completed five rescue flights and four ground transports last week and they continue to work with rescues to network and move out available animals in affected areas.

ü•ò Our General Services Department is hosting a relief supply drive to collect non perishable food items and cleaning supplies for those impacted by Laura! Find out more on our last post.

Jefferson Parish, in partnership with The Blood Center, will be hosting a blood drive tomorrow, Saturday, Aug. 29 at Lakeshore Playground (1125 Rosa Ave., Metairie, LA 70005) from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.

ü©∏ Once donors make an appointment, they should visit ‚ÄúFastlane‚Äù at www.thebloodcenter.org/fastlane after 12:01 a.m. on the day they plan to donate to complete medical questions. All individuals should eat a good meal before donating and bring their ID to the site. When donors arrive to the site, they will have their temperature checked and will be screened for COVID-19 symptoms. Once qualified, they will be assigned a number and be spaced out for social distancing purposes.

Test results for antibody testing will be available after 48 hours. Blood donors must give their email address. They will then be instructed to set up a blood donor account to access their test results. Test results are not given via email, snail mail or phone call, in order to not violate HIPAA regulations.

All curbside garbage and recycling services are cancelled this Monday, August 24, 2020 due to Tropical Storms Laura and Marco.

Residents are advised not to place their garbage cans and recycling bins at the curb for pick up. All garbage and recycling containers should be placed in a secure location away from open spaces.

Any bulk waste material, such as furniture, tree limbs, grass clippings, scrap appliances, waste tires and construction debris should not be placed curbside for bulk waste collection. Bulk waste should be removed from the curb and secured in a safe location so that it does not become a safety hazard and clog storm drains in the event of street flooding. Residents should bundle and tie down all loose trash such as tree limbs and place these materials in a location where debris cannot become hazardous to homes and vehicles in high winds.

post_text:
With the potential threat to Jefferson Parish from Tropical Storm Laura and Tropical Depression #14, the Alario Center drive-thru testing site will suspend services from Monday, August 24 to Tuesday, August 25.

The Alario Center testing site will close because it is supported by the Louisiana Army National Guard and they are shifting operations to storm support.

Currently, impacts for Jefferson Parish include the potential of heavy rainfall. Strong winds and elevated tides could also affect portions of the area depending on the eventual tracks and intensities of the two systems. There is a higher than normal uncertainly in specific impacts and it is important to continue monitoring the latest forecasts for any changes in expected impacts.

For this #TerrificTuesday, we would like to recognize our Jefferson Parish Juvenile Services team, led by Director of Juvenile Services Roy L. Juncker, Jr., for receiving The Merit Award from BGR, which recognizes outstanding performance by public sector employees. Our Juvenile Services employees received this award because of their outstanding administration of the Alternatives to Detention (ATD) program.

The team includes:
-Joan Ruiz, Probation Manager
-Matt Villio, Juvenile Justice Reform Coordinator
-Colleen Conley, Probation Officer III, ATD program
-Lashaunda Thomas, Probation Officer III, ATD program
-Luis Bustamante, Probation Officer III, ATD program
-Trista Duplessis, Probation Officer III, ATD program
-Erin Ronquille, Probation Officer III, ATD program

Each of you have served Jefferson Parish proudly! Congratulations and a job well done! #JeffersonStrong #TerrificTuesday

Jefferson Parish Schools (JP Schools) will delay the start of the 2020-2021 school year to August 26 to coincide with the launch of a COVID-19 rapid testing program for symptomatic JP Schools employees, made possible by Ochsner Hospital for Children.

The rapid testing results will enable JP Schools to quickly determine if an employee has COVID-19 and take the appropriate precautions to mitigate the spread and disruptions to learning. In the coming days, the district will work through the details of this process.

JP Schools will also use the additional two weeks for professional development for teachers and employees and to fine tune its processes for virtual and in-classroom instructional models. Additionally, JP Schools is working with its vendors as it continues to receive student technology and curriculum resources on a rolling basis.

For more information on Jefferson Parish Schools and Start Strong, its return to school plan during the COVID-19 pandemic, visit www.jpschools.org/startstrong

post_text:
Jefferson Parish has announced additional days for COVID-19 mobile testing throughout the Parish. Free walk-up testing is available to anyone who wants to determine his or her COVID-19 status. Testing is available to individuals, age 2 and older. Those who are 65 years of age and older will be able to get a test during the first 45 minutes of testing at each location. Testing at each mobile site is available at the times listed, or until all test kits have been utilized. *Please note that due to the high demand, individuals are encouraged to arrive early. There will be a separate line for individuals 65 years or older.

Testing at Alario Center is available Monday - Saturday from 7 a.m. - 7 p.m. There is no cap on daily testing at this location. Individuals are encouraged to register in advance at www.DoINeedACOVID19Test.com

RLAA is an in-depth look at areas that have experienced multiple losses from flooding. The purpose of a RLAA is to generate specific guidance on mitigation solutions for individual buildings or areas, in contrast to a community-wide approach presented in a hazard mitigation or floodplain management plan.

The progress report is available online at www.jeffparish.net/RLAA.

Visit https://www.jeffparish.net/press-releases for more information.

As we continue to monitor Tropical Storm Hanna, now is the time to prepare. The storm is expected to make landfall in Texas and is producing showers and storms across our area. Some of these storms could produce heavy rainfall and gusty winds.

It‚Äôs important that you have a Hurricane Preparedness Kit ready to go during this time of the year.

Residents should continue to monitor the news for weather updates. Residents are also reminded about the JPALERT System for real-time updates. Residents can text either JPALERT or JPNOTICIAS to 888-777 to stay informed.

A list of tropical weather supplies, evacuation details and other critical information can be found on www.getagameplan.org.

Happy #TerrificTuesday! ‚ú®

Today we want to recognize Tara Hazelbaker, Director of Internal Auditor. Tara recently received an Internal Auditor Certification. The CIA (Certified Internal Auditor) is the primary professional designation offered by The Institute of Internal Auditors, the internal audit profession‚Äôs advocate, educator, standard setter and certifying body. The CIA designation is a globally recognized certification for internal auditors and is a standard by which individuals may demonstrate their competency and professionalism in the internal audit field. To become certified, CIA candidates must meet education, character and work experience requirements and pass three certification exams.

Congratulations Tara for this accomplishment, you have made Jefferson Parish proud!

For this #TerrificTuesday, we would like to recognize the Assistant Director of our Jefferson Parish Emergency Management Department Timothy ‚ÄúTimmy‚Äù Gautreau Jr.

Timmy has been instrumental during the COVID-19 pandemic in setting up and coordinating various testing sites throughout the Parish. He works the Alario Center testing site every day and coordinates with the National Guard and the state to make sure the site is equipped with everything that is needed. Timmy has also been instrumental in getting the mobile testing sites up and running. This is all on top of his daily work providing emergency management planning for Jefferson Parish Departments and agencies and overall emergency management coordination and guidance during major emergencies within the Parish to provide for the continued safety of the citizens and visitors to Jefferson Parish.

If you receive a call from the Louisiana Department of Health, it is important to know if it is the LDH Contact Tracing Team and not a scammer.

If it is the LDH, they will not do the following:
‚Ä¢ask about your finances or other personal information
‚Ä¢ask for your banking information or social security number

To verify you are the person that they are trying to reach, the LDH Contact Tracing Team may ask you to confirm your first name, last name and date of birth. They do this to ensure they are not sharing any personal information with anyone that is not you.

Today, we recognize Juneteenth (short for ‚ÄúJune Nineteeth‚Äù) which honors the end of slavery in the United States and is considered the longest-running African American holiday.

According to the Director of our Water Department Sidney Bazley, ‚ÄúToday is a day to bring awareness of equality for a person not to be judged by the color of their skin... this day celebrates what we should be celebrating every day.‚Äù

Learn more about #juneteenth at juneteenth.com

post_text:
Summertime is officially here and we are already experiencing high heat index days‚òÄÔ∏è

When out running errands, never leave a child or pet in an unattended vehicle. Even if it is not too hot outside, the temperature inside of a vehicle can rise significantly within the first 15 to 30 minutes. Leaving windows cracked does not slow the heating process or decrease the maximum temperature measured inside the vehicle.

For more information, visit the National Weather Service: www.weather.gov/lsx/excessiveheat-automobiles

post_text:
You all know what today is‚Ä¶.#TerrificTuesday! We would like to recognize a Jefferson Parish employee in the Planning Department, Arrington Pickens. Like all departments, the Planning Department had never experienced a pandemic before. As soon as it became apparent what they would be dealing with, high-risk employees were sent home and the staff started working in split teams. It was during this period, Typist Clerk III, Arrington Pickens, really stepped up and learned to do other jobs that were necessary to assist in keep the Planning Department going.

Thank you Arrington Pickens for going above and beyond even during a pandemic to keep the Planning Department going. #JeffersonProud #TerrificTuesday

post_text: Garbage, recycling and bulk waste collection services will resume as regularly scheduled on Tuesday, June 9, 2020 in Unincorporated Jefferson Parish and the Town of Jean Lafitte. There will be no make-up schedule for areas that receive collection on a Monday because of the cancellation of services due to Tropical Storm Cristobal. For residents who have garbage pick-up on Mondays, their collection will resume on Thursday, June 11, 2020. For residents scheduled for recycling or bulk waste collection on a Monday, collection will resume on Monday, June 15, 2020. üóë ‚ôªÔ∏è

post_text:
NOTICE TO ALL RESIDENTS OF UNINCORPORATED JEFFERSON PARISH AND THE TOWN OF JEAN LAFITTE: All curbside garbage and recycling services are cancelled this Monday, June 8, 2020 due to Tropical Storm Cristobal.

The Parish‚Äôs contracted hauler, Waste Connections, will not double back to collect households missed on Monday. Residents are asked to hold their trash and recyclables until the next scheduled collection date. If homeowners are unable to wait until their next scheduled collection date, they may drop their trash off at one of the Parish‚Äôs four drop-off sites once they reopen for business on Tuesday, June 9, 2020.

Regularly scheduled trash, recycling and bulk items collection is anticipated to resume on Tuesday, June 9, 2020.

post_text:
Jefferson Parish President Cynthia Lee Sheng has announced all parish buildings will close on Monday, June 8, 2020 due to Tropical Storm Cristobal.

This includes the Joseph S. Yenni Building, the General Government Building, the 24th Judicial District Court, the First Parish Court, the Second Parish Court, Jefferson Parish Juvenile Court, Jefferson Parish Credit Union, Jefferson Parish libraries and all Jefferson Parish Parks and Recreation activities, including summer camps.

post_text:
Beginning today at 2:00 p.m., Jefferson Transit will suspend all services ahead of Tropical Storm Cristobal.

We would like to emphasize to all riders the importance of making your way home before the suspended service.

Jefferson Transit continues to monitor the weather and will update the public on further service changes as they happen.
